qas.question: What is it called when content is changed from markup to an interactive document?
Browsers typically have plug-ins to support what?
Browsers have you save to disk so they can support what?
What is it called when resources are changed from being unsupported to being downloaded?
What files can be displayed when a file is unsupported?
What unsupported content can resources display that is part of a webpage?

plausible_answers.text: passed to the browser's layout engine to be transformed from markup to an interactive document

qas.question: What process happens to plug-ins saved to disk?

context: In the case of <b4_0>http, https, file, and others<b4_0/>, once the resource has been retrieved the web browser will display it. HTML and associated content (image files, formatting information such as CSS, etc.) is <b6_0>passed to the browser's layout engine to be transformed from markup to an interactive document<b6_0/>, a process known as <b3_0>"<a0_0>rendering<a0_0/>"<b3_0/>. Aside from HTML, web browsers can generally display <b5_0>any kind<b5_0/> of content that can be part of a web page. Most browsers can display images, audio, video, and XML files, and often have plug-ins to support <a1_0><b2_0>Flash applications and Java applets<b2_0/><a1_0/>. Upon encountering a file of an unsupported type or a file that is set up to be downloaded rather than displayed, the browser prompts the user to save the file to disk.
